An Indonesian minister denied that the mud volcano in Java, causing mass evacuations, was linked to his family's drilling company.
Despite experts' warnings of environmental damage, the government struggles to contain the disaster.
The eruption, likely triggered by gas drilling, has led to fatalities and ecological devastation.
Efforts to redirect the mud flow to the sea face skepticism from geologists.
Legal actions are underway to hold responsible parties accountable and provide compensation to affected communities.
President Susilo's pledge to address the crisis with financial aid offers a glimmer of hope amidst the ongoing tragedy.
